13.43	Albigensians	Catharism	Catharism (from Greek: , katharos, pure) was a name given to a Christian religious movement with dualistic and gnostic elements that appeared in the Languedoc region of France and other parts of Europe in the 11th century and flourished in the 12th and 13th centuries. The movement was extinguished in the early decades of the thirteenth century, when the Cathars were persecuted and massacred under the Inquisition.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Talmudtrial.jpg/220px-Talmudtrial.jpg
